  <h1>How to Negotiate Your Severance Package</h1>
  <p class="byline">By <strong>Blake Anders</strong>, Paralegal (employment) &mdash; Contributing Writer, Severance Negotiation. Reviewed by Sloan Whitfield, SHRM-CP. Updated May 2026.</p>

  <p>
    When an employer presents a severance offer, it is almost never their best offer. HR departments routinely open with the company's standard formula — one to two weeks per year of service — knowing that many employees will accept it without question. Negotiating doesn't require a lawyer, an aggressive posture, or even a specific legal claim. It requires preparation, clarity about what you want, and the willingness to ask.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 1: Don't Sign Anything Immediately</h2>
  <p>
    The first rule of severance negotiation is to slow down. Employers often present packages with an implied urgency ("we need this back by Friday") that has no legal basis. If you are 40 or older, federal law (the Older Workers Benefit Protection Act, or OWBPA) guarantees you at least 21 days to review a severance agreement. For younger employees, there's no federal minimum, but most separation agreements contain a review deadline — and that deadline is almost always negotiable.
  </p>
  <p>
    Request the full review period. Use it. Tell HR you'll have a response by the deadline, then use that time to assess the offer, consult an attorney if warranted, and prepare your counter.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 2: Know Your Baseline — Then Benchmark It</h2>
  <p>
    Before you can negotiate, you need to know whether the offer is fair, low, or genuinely generous. Use the <a href="/">Severance Pay Estimator</a> to get a data-driven baseline for your industry, tenure, and salary. If your offer is significantly below the typical range for your industry and years of service, you have clear grounds for a counter. If it's already at the high end, your negotiation energy is better spent on non-cash elements.
  </p>
  <p>
    Also check your offer letter or employment agreement. Some agreements include specific severance language ("employee shall receive X weeks upon involuntary termination") that creates a contractual floor. If you have that language and your offer falls short, point it out in writing.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 3: Identify Your Leverage</h2>
  <p>
    Your leverage in a severance negotiation comes from several potential sources:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Legal claims:</strong> If you believe you were discriminated against (based on age, race, sex, disability, etc.), retaliated against for whistleblowing, or denied protected leave under FMLA, you have potential legal claims. Employers pay more to eliminate legal exposure. You don't need to file a lawsuit — just make clear, professionally, that you're considering your options.</li>
    <li><strong>Institutional knowledge:</strong> If you hold critical knowledge about systems, clients, or processes that will be difficult to transfer, your smooth transition is worth something to your employer. Offer a defined transition period in exchange for an enhanced package.</li>
    <li><strong>Broad non-compete scope:</strong> A restrictive non-compete limits your ability to work. If you're being asked to agree to a sweeping non-compete, that restriction has real economic value to the employer and real cost to you — treat it as a bargaining chip.</li>
    <li><strong>WARN Act non-compliance:</strong> If you're part of a mass layoff and believe proper notice wasn't given, mention that you're looking into WARN Act obligations. Back pay claims are a real risk employers take seriously.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 4: Make Specific, Prioritized Asks</h2>
  <p>
    Don't walk in with a vague request for "more." Prepare a specific list of what you want, ranked by priority, with a brief rationale for each. For example:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Increase cash severance from 8 weeks to 14 weeks (aligning with industry median for my tenure and level)</li>
    <li>Extend COBRA subsidy from 3 months to 6 months</li>
    <li>Accelerate vesting on RSUs scheduled to vest within 90 days</li>
    <li>Reduce non-compete duration from 18 months to 6 months and narrow the geography to a 50-mile radius</li>
    <li>Provide a written positive reference letter</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Lead with your most important ask. Employers often grant the first thing you ask for more readily than a laundry list. If you get what matters most, be prepared to let go of the rest.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 5: Put Your Counter in Writing</h2>
  <p>
    Verbal negotiations leave room for misunderstanding and give the employer deniability. After your initial verbal conversation, follow up with a written email summarizing what you discussed and the specific modifications you are requesting. This creates a paper trail and signals that you are serious and organized — not someone who will back down because the process feels uncomfortable.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 6: Consider an Attorney Consultation</h2>
  <p>
    For packages above $50,000, or any situation involving potential legal claims, a one-hour consultation with an employment attorney is almost always worth the cost ($200–$400). A good employment attorney can quickly identify whether you have claims worth leveraging, flag problematic language in the agreement you might have missed, and coach you on how to present your counter without burning bridges.
  </p>
  <p>
    Many employment attorneys will review a separation agreement for a flat fee. It is a small investment relative to the value of a better outcome.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 7: Know When to Accept</h2>
  <p>
    Negotiation has a point of diminishing returns. Once you have made your asks, received a counter, and pushed back once more, read the room. Employers that have moved significantly from their opening offer have usually reached their practical limit. Continuing to push after a good-faith negotiation can damage your professional relationships and your reference. When you've gotten the best offer you're going to get, accept it clearly and graciously.
  </p>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    This guide is for informational purposes only and does not constitute legal advice. If you believe you have legal claims or your severance situation is complex, consult a licensed employment attorney before responding to any offer.
  </p>
